<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>All About Ferric Oxalate</TITLE>
<META http-equiv=3DContent-Type content=3D"text/html; =
charset=3Diso-8859-1"><LINK=20
href=3D"http://www.bostick-sullivan.com/css.css" type=3Dtext/css =
rel=3Dstylesheet>
<META content=3D"MSHTML 6.00.2900.5945" name=3DGENERATOR></HEAD>
<BODY>
<TABLE cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D"99%" border=3D0>
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD vAlign=3Dtop>
      <TABLE cellSpacing=3D10 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D"99%" border=3D0>
        <TBODY>
        <TR vAlign=3Dtop>
          <TD align=3Dright width=3D"13%">
            <DIV align=3Dright><IMG height=3D50=20
            src=3D"http://www.bostick-sullivan.com/images/spacer.gif"=20
            width=3D50></DIV></TD>
          <TD class=3Dtext width=3D"75%">
            <P class=3Darticletext><SPAN class=3Dheading>All About =
Ferric Oxalate -=20
            How to make etc.</SPAN></P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Ferric oxalate is traditionally given =
the=20
            formula of Fe2(C2O4)3.5H2O. However, according to Dr. =
Michael Ware=20
            ferric oxalate is an =93ill defined=94 compound. It is more =
in line with=20
            ferric ammonium citrate, which does not have a formula in =
the Merck=20
            Index.. Ware, however, does say that the double oxalate =
salts,=20
            (ammonium ferric oxalate, sodium ferric oxalate, etc.) are =
=93well=20
            defined.=94 Ware refers to ferric oxalate as an =
oxalato-ferric=20
            complex.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Ferric oxalate is also known to form =
polymers.=20
            Tests have shown that different precipitation rates produce=20
            differing solubility=92s from the same batch. Free oxalic =
acid in the=20
            ferric oxalate is an issue, especially if one wishes to use =
it for=20
            Kallitype printing where the free oxalic will form an =
insoluble=20
            silver oxalate [Ag2C2O4], sludge that will interfere with =
the=20
            Kallitype process.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>The B+S powdered grade was made with =
a trace=20
            amount of free oxalic acid until 1996. At that time we =
changed to a=20
            new manufacturing procedure which allowed us to make an=20
            exceptionally pure product. Around this time we also began =
supplying=20
            it to a chemical wholesaler who was supplying it to labs and =

            universities who were using it for purposes other than =
platinum=20
            printing and who did not want or need the free oxalic acid =
that was=20
            in the product. </P>
            <P class=3Darticletext><SPAN class=3Darticlesubhead>Ferric =
oxalate and=20
            oxalic acid and color of the solution</SPAN><BR>Ferric =
oxalate will=20
            vary in color according to the amount of oxalic acid =
present. With=20
            little of no oxalic acid it will be a golden amber color. =
With=20
            moderate mounts of oxalic acid it will be a yellow, with =
large=20
            amounts it will turn fluorescent green.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>The following are procedures for =
testing and=20
            making ferric oxalate.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext><SPAN class=3Darticlesubhead>Testing =
for free=20
            oxalic acid:</SPAN><BR>Add 1 drop of a 10% to 20% silver =
nitrate to=20
            a 2 ml sample of the ferric oxalate solution. If a white =
precipitate=20
            is formed, this is silver oxalate, and indicates that there =
is free=20
            oxalic acid present. One can verify this test by adding a =
drop of=20
            10% oxalic acid to the sample and then adding the silver =
nitrate=20
            again. Note that the ferric oxalate solution should be at =
room=20
            temperature when the test is made.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext><SPAN class=3Darticlesubhead>Testing =
for ferrous=20
            oxalate</SPAN><BR>Ferrous oxalate is the result of the decay =
by=20
            light or age of ferric oxalate. This causes the =
precipitation of the=20
            platinum or palladium metal that forms the image in a =
platinum=20
            print. Your ferric oxalate should be relatively free of =
ferrous for=20
            good printmaking.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>There is a traditional test for the =
presence of=20
            ferrous oxalate. This involves testing with potassium =
ferricyanide.=20
            This test is unreliable in that it gives false positives =
when EDTA=20
            has been added. It also can produce a cyan color when the =
material=20
            is still acceptable for making prints.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>A better test is to make a fog test =
by coating=20
            a piece of paper and developing without any exposure. If =
there is a=20
            gray tint to the coated part of the paper after clearing, =
the ferric=20
            oxalate has turned bad.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext><SPAN class=3Darticlesubhead>Removing =
free oxalic=20
            acid.</SPAN><BR>You can add small quantities of ferric =
nitrate with=20
            stirring. Re-test after each addition of ferric nitrate. =
This method=20
            will leave a minute amount of nitric acid in the solution. =
It is=20
            harmless health wise but it is a oxidizer like chlorate, =
etc., that=20
            it could in sufficient quantities make the ferric oxalate=20
            contrastier.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext><SPAN =
class=3Darticlesubhead>Dissolving ferric=20
            oxalate</SPAN><BR>There are several ways to do this:<BR>1. =
Add water=20
            and stir. Now stir every few hours until it is dissolved. =
This may=20
            take as long as 12 to 24 hours.<BR>2. Zap it in the micro =
wave.=20
            Loosen cap and give the bottle 10 seconds zaps with shaking =
between=20
            zaps. Zap it until it is hot to hold.<BR>3. If you are lucky =
enough=20
            to have a laboratory hotplate stirrer, this will work dandy. =
Set the=20
            temp to about 140 Deg F.<BR>Older texts warn of using heat =
as it=20
            will cause the generation of ferrous oxalate. This may have =
due to=20
            the impurities in older versions of the product. We have =
found that=20
            it will take quite a bit of heat with decaying into =
ferrous.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext><SPAN class=3Darticlesubhead>The =
double ferric=20
            oxalates -- For Ziatypes</SPAN><BR><SPAN =
class=3Darticlesubhead>Sodium=20
            ferric oxalate</SPAN></P>
            <TABLE cellSpacing=3D10 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D"99%" =
border=3D0>
              <TBODY>
              <TR>
                <TD>ferric oxalate</TD>
                <TD>6.7 gm</TD></TR>
              <TR>
                <TD>sodium oxalate</TD>
                <TD>5.9 gm</TD></TR>
              <TR>
                <TD>water</TD>
                <TD>40.00 ml</TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
            <P class=3Darticletext>The solution will turn cold and may =
need to be=20
            heated to dissolve and clear the liquor. If still too cloudy =

            cautiously add small quantities of water.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext><SPAN class=3Darticlesubhead>Sodium =
ferric=20
            oxalate method 2</SPAN><BR>Sodium oxalate can be made in =
solution,=20
            so another way to make the sodium ferric oxalate is: </P>
            <TABLE cellSpacing=3D10 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D"99%" =
border=3D0>
              <TBODY>
              <TR>
                <TD>oxalic acid</TD>
                <TD>3.9 gm</TD></TR>
              <TR>
                <TD>sodium carbonate anhydrous</TD>
                <TD>4.6 gm</TD></TR>
              <TR>
                <TD>water</TD>
                <TD>40.0 ml</TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Dissolve the oxalic acid and slowly =
add the=20
            carbonate<BR>(Lots of harmless bubbling and fizzing goes on =
so do=20
            this in a 200 ml beaker otherwise it will look like and =
explosion in=20
            a root beer factory.)<BR>You now have 5.3 gm of sodium =
oxalate in=20
            solution<BR><BR>Now add</P>
            <TABLE cellSpacing=3D10 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D"99%" =
border=3D0>
              <TBODY>
              <TR class=3Dsmalltxt>
                <TD height=3D12>ferric oxalate powder</TD>
                <TD>6.7 gm</TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Stir and gently heat until dissolved =
and is=20
            bright green. It is ready to use. If it is dirty looking and =
not a=20
            bright green, add tiny amounts of oxalic acid until it turns =
a nice=20
            green.<BR><BR><SPAN class=3Darticlesubhead>For the rest of =
these I=20
            will just cite the quantities and chemicals. Follow the =
procedure as=20
            above.</SPAN><BR><SPAN class=3Darticlesubhead>Lithium ferric =

            oxalate:</SPAN><BR>This is a very interesting creature. =
Makes a=20
            sharper cooler brown which is a lot closer to the standard =
palladium=20
            brown obtained by the developing out procedure. It is also =
at least=20
            one paper grade higher in contrast than ammonium ferric =
oxalate. It=20
            takes longer to print. I made a print and added 1 drop of 2% =
AD and=20
            it went crazy, right off the map in contrast and lots and =
lots of=20
            grain and the color was blue-black. It looks like you need a =
.1 % to=20
            a .5% AD for this puppy.</P>
            <TABLE cellSpacing=3D10 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D"99%" =
border=3D0>
              <TBODY>
              <TR class=3Dsmalltxt>
                <TD height=3D12>ferric oxalate </TD>
                <TD>6.7 gm</TD></TR>
              <TR class=3Dsmalltxt>
                <TD height=3D12>lithium oxalate</TD>
                <TD>4.4 gm</TD></TR>
              <TR class=3Dsmalltxt>
                <TD height=3D12>water</TD>
                <TD>40.0 ml</TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
            <P class=3Darticletext><SPAN class=3Darticlesubhead>Lithium =
ferric=20
            oxalate method 2.</SPAN><BR>Lithium oxalate can be made in =
solution=20
            thusly:</P>
            <TABLE cellSpacing=3D10 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D"99%" =
border=3D0>
              <TBODY>
              <TR class=3Dsmalltxt>
                <TD height=3D12>lithium carbonate*</TD>
                <TD>4.0 gm</TD></TR>
              <TR class=3Dsmalltxt>
                <TD height=3D12>oxalic acid</TD>
                <TD>5.6 gm</TD></TR>
              <TR class=3Dsmalltxt>
                <TD height=3D12>water</TD>
                <TD>40.0 ml</TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
            <P class=3Darticletext><BR>You can now add </P>
            <TABLE cellSpacing=3D10 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D"99%" =
border=3D0>
              <TBODY>
              <TR class=3Dsmalltxt>
                <TD height=3D12>ferric oxalate powder</TD>
                <TD>6.7 gm</TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
            <P class=3Darticletext>and proceed as above.<BR>(*Lithium =
carbonate is=20
            expensive from chemical supply houses but can be gotten =
cheap from=20
            ceramic supply houses. It is used as a flux in glazes. I =
bought 5=20
            lbs for $20.00, Spectrum wants $50.00 per 500 gm for =
practical grade=20
            which is the same as the ceramic supply house.)</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext><SPAN class=3Darticlesubhead>Ammonium =
ferric=20
            oxalate:</SPAN><BR></P>
            <TABLE cellSpacing=3D10 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D"99%" =
border=3D0>
              <TBODY>
              <TR class=3Dsmalltxt>
                <TD height=3D12>ammonium oxalate</TD>
                <TD>5.4 gm</TD></TR>
              <TR class=3Dsmalltxt>
                <TD height=3D12>ferric oxalate</TD>
                <TD>6.7 gm</TD></TR>
              <TR class=3Dsmalltxt>
                <TD height=3D12>water</TD>
                <TD>40.0 ml</TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
            <P class=3Darticletext><BR><SPAN =
class=3Darticlesubhead>Ammonium=20
            oxalate</SPAN><BR>To make: neutralize oxalic acid with =
strong=20
            ammonium or ammonium carbonate, filter and dry the=20
            crystals.<BR><SPAN class=3Darticlesubhead><BR>Procedure for =
making=20
            ferric oxalate*</SPAN><BR>This procedure requires a modest =
amount of=20
            chemical skills and prudent safety precautions should be=20
            observed.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Take 200 gm of ferric ammonium =
sulfate=20
            [FeCH4NO8S2] and dissolve in 300 ml water in a 500 ml =
beaker.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Add 100 ml of strong ammonium =
hydroxide [880=20
            Ammonia] and stir. (Caution the ammonia is strong and =
ghastly, do=20
            this in a well-ventilated area.) When the ammonia is added, =
a=20
            mud-like gelatinous precipitate will be formed. This is iron =

            hydrate, which is actually just iron in water.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Keeping adding the ammonia until no =
new=20
            precipitate is formed. Too much ammonia won=92t =
hurt.<BR>This next=20
            step is to wash the gel. You will want to get out the excess =
ammonia=20
            and sulfates from the gel. This is a little tricky.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>First let the mud settle to the =
bottom of your=20
            beaker. This may take an hour or so. Carefully pour off the =
clear=20
            solution on top.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Now add more water to bring it to the =

            approximate level as before decanting. Do this 3 more times. =
On the=20
            last time do not add more water.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Now take a 1 foot square piece of an =
old tee=20
            shirt or bed sheet and drape it over another beaker forming =
a=20
            pocket. Attach the fabric around the beaker with a large =
heavy=20
            rubber band.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext><SPAN class=3Darticleital>Make sure =
you have your=20
            gloves on at this point!</SPAN></P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Now pour and scoop out the washed mud =
from the=20
            beaker into the pocket.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Remove the rubber band and form a =
pouch of the=20
            fabric with the mud inside.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>With gloved hands take the pouch and =
twist the=20
            ends wringing out any water from the mud. Of course do it =
over a=20
            sink. The juice squeezed out can go down the drain. Be =
careful if=20
            the fabric is old as it can rip or burst.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Replace the pouch back to an empty =
beaker,=20
            fastening with the rubber band as you had originally =
done.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Pour @ 400 ml of water through the =
mud in the=20
            pouch. The pouch will now be suspended in the water.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Remove and squeeze as before.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Replace in the beaker with the rubber =
band as=20
            before. You are now ready to make your ferric oxalate =
solution.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext><SPAN =
class=3Darticlesubhead>Dissolving the=20
            mud</SPAN><BR>You don't need to measure the oxalic acid, you =
will be=20
            doing this by inspection.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Slowly begin adding the dry oxalic =
acid to the=20
            mud in the pouch. You should soon see some of the =93mud=94 =
begin to=20
            dissolve. The resulting liquid is ferric oxalate. </P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Keep adding oxalic acid and gently =
stirring=20
            with a plastic spoon. As you add it, you will continue to =
see the=20
            mud go into solution. Eventually it will begin to drip =
through the=20
            cloth into the beaker.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Continue until you have used up about =
90% of=20
            your original =93mud.=94 You don=92t want to go any further =
or you risk=20
            putting in excess oxalic acid.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Remove and discard the pouch.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>The liquid should be a bright yellow =
green.=20
            This is your ferric oxalate. It should be approximately =
27%.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>If is it cloudy, take a small sample =
and add a=20
            tiny quantity of oxalic to the sample. If it clears up, the=20
            cloudiness is ferric hydrate and you can proceed to add and =
stir in=20
            small quantities of oxalic acid to the solution in main =
beaker until=20
            it has cleared up. Alternately you can filter the hydrate =
out with a=20
            filter and filter paper.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>You may now want to test for free =
oxalic acid=20
            as shown above.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Now clean up your room =96 it=92s =
messy! There=92ll=20
            be red yukky all over the place.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>I=92ve published various versions of =
this paper=20
            over the last 20 years. This is the latest go-round. I =
printed=20
            several 50 print Harry Smith portfolios using this method of =
making=20
            ferric oxalate back in the early 80=92s. With care you can =
make an=20
            excellent grade ferric oxalate in one afternoon.</P>
            <P class=3Darticletext>Now go play with your ferric =
oxalate.<BR></P>
            <P class=3Darticletext><SPAN =
class=3Darticlesubhead>Notes:</SPAN>=20
            <BR>*If you are lucky enough to have a Buchner filter, =
vacuum flask,=20
            and an aspirator this will help quite a bit. Probably worth =
the=20
            approximate $100.00 investment if you plan to use ferric =
oxalate=20
            regularly. Any good chemistry lab techniques textbook will =
explain=20
            its use.<BR><BR><BR>-- Dick Sullivan</P></TD>
          <TD class=3Dtext vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dright width=3D"12%"><IMG =
height=3D50=20
            src=3D"http://www.bostick-sullivan.com/images/spacer.gif"=20
        width=3D50></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
      <P =
class=3Dsmalltxt>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></BODY></HTML>

